content:
This file defines the core type structures used throughout the DocMed repository. These types provide a clear and consistent way to represent data related to documentation entries, files, commit history, and user interface views.

## Key Exports

*   **`ManifestEntry`**: Represents a single entry in the documentation manifest.
    *   `filePath`: The path to the documentation file.
    *   `title`: The human-readable title of the document.
    *   `docKey`: A unique identifier for the document, often derived from its path.

*   **`DocFile`**: Represents a complete documentation file, including its content.
    *   `filePath`: The path to the documentation file.
    *   `title`: The human-readable title of the document.
    *   `content`: The actual markdown or text content of the document.

*   **`Commit`**: Represents a Git commit.
    *   `id`: The unique SHA-1 hash of the commit.
    *   `message`: The commit message.
    *   `pusher`: The name of the user who pushed the commit.
    *   `timestamp`: The date and time the commit was made.

*   **`View`**: Represents different possible views within the application.
    *   `type`: Discriminator string indicating the type of view. Can be one of:
        *   `"home"`: The main dashboard or landing page.
        *   `"commits"`: A view displaying commit history.
        *   `"doc"`: A view displaying a specific documentation page.
    *   `key`: (Required for `"doc"` type) The `docKey` of the document to display.

*   **`Tab`**: Represents a tab in the user interface.
    *   `id`: A unique identifier for the tab.
    *   `view`: The `View` object that this tab navigates to.
    *   `label`: The text displayed on the tab.

## Usage Example

These types are fundamental for defining the shapes of data handled by various parts of the application, such as state management, API responses, and component props. For instance, when fetching and displaying a document, you might use these types:

```typescript
// Assuming you have a function that fetches a document
async function loadDocument(docKey: string): Promise<DocFile> {
  // ... fetch logic ...
  return { filePath: 'docs/introduction.md', title: 'Introduction', content: '# Welcome!' };
}

// Example usage within a component or service
const targetDocKey = 'introduction';
loadDocument(targetDocKey)
  .then(docFile => {
    console.log(`Loaded document: ${docFile.title}`);
    // Further processing or rendering of docFile.content
  })
  .catch(error => {
    console.error('Error loading document:', error);
  });

// Example of defining a tab that navigates to a document
const myTab: Tab = {
  id: 'intro-tab',
  view: { type: 'doc', key: 'introduction' },
  label: 'Introduction',
};
```
